  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "husHfYkGe9wOocHiMyZNgRHL/fs=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\nOn every new ordinal beyond the outbox cursor, SwarmChannel pushes operations via: serialize \u2192 encrypt \u2192 /bytes upload \u2192 feed write \u2192 manifest update \u2192 cursor advance.\n\n## Step-by-step\n1. SyncManager detects new ordinals in `operation_index_operations` beyond the outbox cursor.\n2. Ops are grouped by `(documentId, scope, branch)` into `SyncOperation` objects.\n3. Each `SyncOperation` is added to `SwarmChannel.outbox`.\n4. `outbox.onAdded` fires, running:\n   - serialize to JSON\n   - encrypt with AES-256-GCM (wallet-derived key)\n   - upload to `/bytes` endpoint on the Bee node\n   - write the reference to the document's feed (SOC)\n   - update the drive manifest feed\n   - call `syncOp.executed()` \u2014 SyncManager advances the cursor in `sync_cursors`.\n\n## Why this ordering matters\nThe cursor only advances after the feed write succeeds, so a mid-push failure leaves the outbox ready to retry the same batch on next cycle \u2014 no data loss, no duplicates.\n\n## Source\nSwarm Channel Architecture, \"Push Cycle (local \u2192 Swarm)\"; `adapter/src/channel/swarm-channel.ts`.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
